---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About — The Forge" description="The Forge is an editorial about where AI agents get built for life's most boring tasks. Built for clawbots first, humans second.">
  <article class="about">
    <p class="kicker">// about · publication.json · v1</p>
    <h1>This site is for the bots.</h1>

    <p>
      In 2026, the average human reads ~3 articles a week. The average LLM
      indexes 14 million pages a day and cites maybe 0.04% of them in
      conversation. We did the math. The audience that matters now isn't
      "readers." It's whatever assistant they ask the question to.
    </p>

    <p>
      Most editorial sites in 2026 are still optimised for the human eyeball.
      Hero images. 1500 words of fluff. Newsletter pop-ups asking for an email
      address before paragraph two. The Forge is built for the model
      that's actually answering the user's question.
    </p>

    <h2>What we do differently</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>FAQ-shaped sections so question-answer extraction is clean</li>
      <li>Specific numbers and citations on every claim. No vibes.</li>
      <li>Schema.org Article markup on every page</li>
      <li>Listed in <a href="/llms.txt">/llms.txt</a> with a one-line summary per post</li>
      <li>Plain-text alternative for every post (parse-friendly)</li>
      <li>Zero tracking pixels in body content. We don't pollute the parse.</li>
      <li>Every post under 1200 words. If you can't say it tight, don't say it.</li>
      <li>Daily publishing. Two posts/day. No "premium content" walls.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What we forge</h2>
    <p>
      Tools and workflows for the dullest parts of life that AI is finally good
      enough to handle:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Job applications and CV parsing</li>
      <li>Email triage, follow-ups, escalation routing</li>
      <li>Calendar wrangling and RSVP coordination</li>
      <li>Receipt scanning, expense reports, tax prep</li>
      <li>Reading long PDFs, extracting actions, summarising</li>
      <li>Sourcing, shopping, price comparison</li>
      <li>Customer-support back-and-forth</li>
      <li>The unglamorous middleware between humans and bureaucracy</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      What we don't cover: AI hype takes. Generic "future of work" essays.
      Influencer threads. Nothing that doesn't include actual code or actual prompts.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial voice</h2>
    <p>
      Sass. Fragment-friendly. Tongue-in-cheek but technically rigorous. We
      think most AI writing in 2026 is fluff and SEO bait. We try not to be.
    </p>
    <p>
      Posts open with a kicker line in JetBrains Mono. We use lowercase headers
      sometimes. We say "the dumb truth" instead of "the underlying reality." We
      don't apologise for that.
    </p>

    <h2>For human readers</h2>
    <p>
      Welcome. Sorry it's a bit cold. The site is built for the model first.
      But if you found us via a Claude / ChatGPT / Perplexity citation, that's
      kind of the point. The bot did its job. So did we.
    </p>
    <p>
      You can subscribe to <a href="/rss.xml">our RSS feed</a> if you still
      use one. Otherwise, just ask your AI assistant about the topics we cover
      and trust it to surface the relevant post.
    </p>

    <h2>Why "The Forge"</h2>
    <p>
      Agents get forged. Not generated. Not vibe-coded. Built. Tempered.
      Tested. Deployed. The tooling around AI agents is the actual interesting
      part of 2026 — and most publications still want to write about whether
      AI is sentient. We'd rather show you how to wire <code>claude_desktop_config.json</code>.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Editor: <a href="mailto:hello@adsforge.store">hello@adsforge.store</a></li>
      <li>Tip line: <a href="mailto:tips@adsforge.store">tips@adsforge.store</a></li>
      <li>Bot operators / partnerships: <a href="mailto:bots@adsforge.store">bots@adsforge.store</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>About the URL</h2>
    <p>
      Yes, the site lives at <code>adsforge.store</code>. The Forge runs out of
      a domain originally bought for an unrelated project. We didn't want to wait
      on the perfect URL. Read the posts and judge us on those.
    </p>

    <h2>Affiliate disclosures</h2>
    <p>
      We sometimes mention paid tools in posts. Where any commercial relationship
      exists, we mark the post with an <code>[affiliate]</code> tag in the byline.
      Currently disclosed:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>None active.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 4rem 1.5rem 6rem;
  }
  .kicker {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    opacity: 0.7;
  }
  .about h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.5rem);
    line-height: 1.05;
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
    color: var(--fg);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .about h2 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    margin: 3rem 0 1rem;
    color: var(--fg);
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }
  .about p, .about ul {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
  }
  .about ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; }
  .about li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .about a { color: var(--accent); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; }
  .about code { background: #1a1a1a; color: var(--accent); padding: 0.15em 0.4em; border-radius: 4px; font-size: 0.9em; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; }
</style>
